These predicted siRNAs were then screened by the following criteria  for finding the most efficient ones:    A) Homology search  To minimize the chance of off-target ef- fects, the most widely used algorithm, BLAST   (http://blast.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov) was applied in this study.

We evaluated the thermodynamic features  of candidate siRNAs using Sfold software  (http://sfold.wadsworth.org) which includes a statistical sampling algorithm to produce a probability profiling of single stranded re-gions in RNA secondary structure  14,32 and  Genbee service (http://www.genebee.msu.su/ services/rna2_reduced.html).

For this purpose, we ap- plied some web-based search tools which are available for identification of all anticipated seed matches for any given siRNA sequence in following URLs  22: http://informaticseski  tis.griffith.edu.au/SpecificityServer, http://www.dharmacon.com/seedlocator/default.aspx   Candidate siRNAs which had the least pos- sible seed homology were selected.
